Help and packages

You can ask for help 

help(sum)
?seq

  • You can access basic function (e.g, sum, mean, variance and others) that come with base R.

  • For more complex or specific task you can use functions/data sets that have been created and that are implemented in packages.

install.packages("packagename")

Help and packages

  • dplyr

R creating objects

  • Everything in R is an object.

  • To create a object use the following syntax:

x = 20
x <- 20 # this is a comment and '<-' produces the same result as '='
x = c(10,20,30) # combining values

Use functions for the objects: 

mean(x)

[1] 20

var(x)

[1] 100

sum(x)

[1] 60

Data Types and Structures

R has many data structures. These include:

  • atomic vectors
  • list
  • matrix
  • data frame
  • arrays

Atomic Vectors

  • A vector is the most common and basic data structure in R
x = c(1,2,3,4,5) #numerical vector
y =  c("Sarah", "Tracy", "Jon") # vector of character
y = c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE) # logical vector

Data Types and Structures

Matrix and Data frame

  • The best way to understand what is a matrix and a data frame is understanding how the vectors could be grouped.

  • Ex:

x = c(1,2)
y = c(1,3)
z = c("Brazil", "Argentina")

matrix(c(x,y),2,2)

     [,1] [,2]
[1,]    1    1
[2,]    2    3

data.frame(x,y,z)

  x y         z
1 1 1    Brazil
2 2 3 Argentina

Genomic Data sets 

x = c("snp1","snp2", "snp3", "snp4", "snp5", "snp6")
y = c(1,1,2,2,3,3)
z = c(10,20,100,400,150,200)
ind1 = c("AA", "AA", "aa", "Aa", "aa", "AA")
ind2 = c("AA", "AA", "aa", "Aa", "AA", "AA")
ind3 = c("Aa", "AA", "aa", "Aa", "Aa", "aa")
ind4 = c("aa", "AA", "Aa", "aa", "AA", "AA")

snp_data = data.frame(name = x,chr = y,pos = z,ind1,ind2,ind3,ind4)

Subsetting Data

  • Select only snp1:
snp_data[1,] # selection the first row

  name chr pos ind1 ind2 ind3 ind4
1 snp1   1  10   AA   AA   Aa   aa
  • Select only ind1:
snp_data[,4] # selection the col indicating ind 1

[1] AA AA aa Aa aa AA
Levels: aa Aa AA
  • Delete rows and col:
snp_data[,-2] # deleting the chr info

  name pos ind1 ind2 ind3 ind4

Population Genetics Summary

Allele Frequencie

\[ f(A_1) = p_j = \dfrac{\#A_1}{2N} \]

\[ f(A_2) = q_j = 1-p_j \]

nA1 = sum(maize.hyb[,1])
N = length(maize.hyb[,1])
p_1 = nA1/(2*N)
q_1 = 1-p_1
p_1

[1] 0.93

q_1

[1] 0.07

Population Genetics Summary

Allele Frequencie

p <- colMeans(maize.hyb, na.rm = T)/2
q=1-p
hist(p)

Population Genetics Summary

Observed and expected heterozygosity

\[ H_0= \dfrac{\#H_j}{N} \]

\[ H_e = 2p_jq_j \]

nA12 = sum(maize.hyb[,1]==1)
N = length(maize.hyb[,1])
h0_1 = nA12/N #obs Het
h0_1

[1] 0.1

he_1 =2* p_1 * q_1 #exp het
he_1

[1] 0.1302

Hobs <- colMeans(maize.hyb== 1, na.rm = T)
Hesp <- 2*p*q

Population Genetics Summary

Checking HWE

Expectation = c(aa =q_1^2, Aa = 2*p_1*q_1, AA=p_1^2) * N
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
barplot(round(Expectation), main="Expectation")
barplot(table(maize.hyb[,1]), main="Observed")


chisq.test(table(maize.hyb[,1]),p=Expectation/N) #H0:HWE vs. Ha:noHWE


    Chi-squared test for given probabilities

data:  table(maize.hyb[, 1])
X-squared = 2.6901, df = 2, p-value = 0.2605

Homework/Quiz 1

Objectives:

  • Most important: get experience with R !

  • Estimate population genetic parameters in a real data set.

  • Interpret the results in a breeding program context.

Population Genetics Summary

Homework/Quiz 1

1) Read the paper and download the genotyping data for the whole set of accessions (Additional File 2) : https://bmcgenomics.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12864-017-3805-4

  • Save the file in a csv format.
  • Use the read.csv command in R to import the data.

2) Produce a table similar to the Table 1 in the paper:

  • Use the concepts of subsetting data presented in the class.
  • Have you tried the dplyr package?

3) Transform the data in the 012 format

  • Function raw.data from the snpReady package
  • Use the arguments call.rate = 0.1 and maf=0.0001 to mantain all markers.
snp012 = raw.data(snp.data, frame = "wide", 
               base=TRUE,  imput = FALSE,
               call.rate = 0.1, maf=0.0001)

Population Genetics Summary

Homework/Quiz 1

4) Describe the markers information. You can use graphics to help you.

  • Any marker with maf<0.05?
  • Any marker with a high number of missing data?
  • Check the Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium statistic for each marker.

5) Compute the population genetic values implemented in the snpReady package. Compare the values with the results presented in the original paper. Discuss the global value of H0 and inbreeding coefficient computed.

6) Based on this data set, try to compute another population metric that might be important to describe the population. It may be one of the metrics already described in the paper (e.g., Fst, dendrogram, linkage disequilibrium) or any other that you judge important. Show the codes used to compute it and discuss an eventual importance of the proposed analysis in the context of the paper.

General Tips

  • If you have experience in R, I would recommend you to write your report using the RMarkdown.

  • You can use the same packages used in the original paper or in the class, but we are encouraging you to go beyond! R is rich in packages and methodologies for Population Genetic studies!

  • The R community is strong and active on the internet. Do not be afraid to use Google and ask for help!
